{"cursor":"12402","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":", co-author of the seminal cognitive science paper \"What the Frog's Eye Tells\nthe Frog's Brain\" (1959)]]\n\n'Walter Harry Pitts, Jr.' (23 April 1923 â 14 May 1969) was a logician who\nworked in the field of cognitive psychology. Smalheiser, Neil R. [http://muse.jhu.edu/login?uri=/journ-\nals/perspectives_in_biology_and_medicine/v043/43.2smalheiser.html \"Walter\nPitts\"], Perspectives in Biology and Medicine, Volume 43, Number 2, Winter 2000,\npp. 217-226, The Johns Hopkins University Press\n\nHe proposed landmark theoretical formulations of neural activity and emergent\nprocesses that influenced diverse fields such as cognitive sciences and\npsychology, philosophy, neurosciences, computer science, artificial neural\nnetworks, cybernetics and artificial intelligence, together with what has come\nto be known as the generative sciences. He is best remembered for having written\nalong with Warren McCulloch, a seminal paper entitled \"A Logical Calculus of\nIdeas Immanent in Nervous Activity\" (1943). This paper proposed the first\nmathematical model of a neural network. The unit of this model, a simple\nformalized neuron, is still the standard of reference in the field of neural\nnetworks. It is often called a McCullochâPitts neuron.\n","linknr":283,"url":"Walter_Pitts","recorded":1376420635,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Walter_Pitts&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Walter_Pitts&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Walter_Pitts","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vect